This paper is primarily focused on computer vision (CV) and specifically on crowd counting, which is a subfield of CV. Therefore, cs.CV is the most likely sub-category. The paper also extensively uses deep neural networks (DNNs) for density regression, which falls under the category of artificial intelligence (AI), making cs.AI the second likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the effectiveness and efficiency of the proposed method, which suggests that machine learning (ML) techniques such as deep learning and neural networks are used, making cs.LG the third likely sub-category. The paper also mentions the datasets used for evaluation, which are related to multimedia (MM), making cs.MM the fourth likely sub-category. Finally, the paper uses a perspective-aware approach to crowd counting, which involves learning weights at every pixel of the maps, suggesting the use of optimization techniques such as neural evolution (NE), making cs.NE the fifth likely sub-category.
